.

We are pleased to dedicate this new bat to Meredith and David Happold (Canberra, 
Australia
) (
Fig. 9
) in recognition of their studies on African bats, and particularly of their monumental work for the Mammals of Africa volume IV on hedgehogs, shrews, and bats (
Happold and Happold, 2013
). As a vernacular name we propose ‘Happolds’ Pipistrelle’.

Specimen ZFMK-MAM-2009.0032, the only specimen caught in gallery forest on the more arid eastern side of the Simandou Ridge, is lighter on the belly, but the other specimens are brown. Cranially, the four species are quite similar. Differences are mainly due to the length of the rostrum (
Fig. 9
).
